    "updated_at": "2013-07-30T12:31:24Z",
    "body": "The `vec::each`/`.each` functions have disappeared, but the problem seems to be that the two signatures were:\n\n``` rust\nfn each<'r, T>(v: &'r [T] ,f: &fn(&'r T) -> bool) -> bool { ... }\nimpl<'self, T> BaseIter<T> for &'self [T] { \n    fn each<'r>(&'r self, &fn(&'r T) -> bool) -> bool { ... }\n}\n```\n\nSo, for the method, the references passed to the vector only last as long as the `self` reference, not the contents of the vector.\n\nThe following reproduces the issue:\n\n``` rust\nstruct Foo<'self>(&'self int);\n\nimpl<'self> Foo<'self> {\n    fn works(&self) -> &'self int { **self }\n\n    fn doesnt<'a>(&'a self) -> &'a int { **self }\n}\n\nfn run<'a>(foo: Foo<'a>) -> &'a int {\n    foo.doesnt()\n}\n\nfn main() {}\n```\n\nI have this feeling that this is unavoidable, but it would be nice to work around e.g. I've met this trying to replace the `StrSlice` trait with default methods on `Str`; which would allow \"custom\" string types to be first class, i.e. `my_custom_string.slice(x, y)` rather than `my_custom_string.as_slice().slice(x, y)`.\n\nIs this a WONT-/CANT-FIX @nikomatsakis?\n",
